import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib as mpl
import numpy as np
%matplotlib inline

# plot
plt.plot([1,2,3,4,10])

plt.plot drew a line plot. it is default behavior. This format is a short hand combination of {color} {marker} {line}.

* 'r*--' : red stars with dashed lines
* 'ks.' : black squares with dotted line (k stands for black)
* 'bD-.' : blue diamonds with dash-dot line.
Plotting another set of 5 points of different color in the same figure.

plt.figure(figsize=(10,7))
plt.plot([1,2,3,4,5], [2,3,4,6, 8], 'bo', label='blue')
plt.plot([1,2,3,4,5], [3,4,5,7,10], 'r*-', label='red')
plt.title('Simple scatter')
plt.xlabel('X')
plt.ylabel('Y')
plt.xlim(0,6)
plt.ylim(0,12)
plt.show()

* Color: 

blue:	b ,green:	g ,red:	r, cyan:	c, magenta:	m,  yellow:	y, black:	k,  white:	w

I want the points drawn on different subplots (axes). I have to call the plot function in the respective axes (ax1 and ax2) instead of plt. Below code, ax1.plot() and ax2.plot() instead of calling plt.plot() twice.

# Create figure and subplots
fit, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(10, 5), sharey=True, dpi=80)

# plot
ax1.plot([1,2,3,4,5], [2,3,4,7,9], 'bo')
ax2.plot([1,2,3,4,5], [3,4,5,7, 10], 'r*')

# title, X and Y labels, X and Y lim
ax1.set_title('Scatter plot - Blue')
ax2.set_title('Scatter plot - Red')
ax1.set_xlabel('X-axis')
ax1.set_ylabel('Y-aixs')
ax2.set_xlabel('X')
ax2.set_ylabel('Y')
ax1.set_xlim(0,6); ax1.set_ylim(0,11)
ax2.set_xlim(0,6); ax2.set_ylim(0,11)

# ax2.yaixs.set_ticks_postion('none')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
Setting 'shary=True'  in plot.subplots() shares the Y axis between toe two subplot. dpi is increase the number of dots per inch of the plot. I can drwo this instead of it using below operations.

fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(10,5), sharey=True)

ax1.plot([1,2,3,4,5], [2,3,4,5,6], 'bo')
ax2.plot([1,2,3,4,5], [3,4,5,6,7], 'r*')

# title, xlabel, ylabel, xlim, ylim
ax1.set(title='Scatter plot Blue', xlabel='X', ylabel='Y', xlim=(0, 6), ylim=(0,10))
ax2.set(title='Scatter plot Red', xlabel='X', ylabel='Y', xlim=(0,6), ylim=(0,10))

plt.show()

A stem plot has vertical line using 'linefmt' at each x location from the baseline to y, and places a marker there using markerfmt. A horizontal line at zero is plotted using basefmt.

x = np.linspace(0.2, 2 * np.pi, 10)

plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
plt.title('Stem plot')
plt.stem(x, np.sin(x), '-.')
plt.show()

Make a pie chart of array x. The fractional area of each wedge is given by x/sum(x). If sum(x) <= 1, then the values of x give the fractional area directly and the array will not be normalized. The wedges are plotted counterclockwise, by default starting from the x-axis.

labels = ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D']
size = [15, 30, 45, 10]
colors=['blue', 'red', 'green', 'yellow']
explode = (0, 0.2, 0, 0)

plt.title('Pie Chart')
plt.pie(size, explode = explode, labels = labels, colors = colors, autopct='%1.1f%%', shadow=True, startangle=90)
plt.axis('equal')
plt.show()

np.random.seed(0)
x = np.random.randn(1000)
plt.title('Histogram')
arrays, bins, patches = plt.hist(x, bins=10)
plt.show()
## Modify the Axis Ticks postions and labels

1. Tick Label: Using 'plt.xticks()' or 'ax.setxticks()' and 'ax.setxticklabel()'


2. Axis's ticks (top/bottom/ left/ right) : Using 'plt.tick_params()'


3. Functional formatting of Tick Labels

* If we are using 'ax', we can use 'ax.set_xticks()' and 'ax.set_xticklabels()' to set the positions and label texts.


* If we are using the 'plt', we can set both the positions as well as the label text in one call using the 'plt.xticks()'

The code of plt.xticks() method, it calls ax.set_xticks() and ax.set_xticklabels() to do the job. plt.xticks takes the ticks and labels as required parameters but I can also adjust the labels fontsize, rotation, horizontalalignment and verticalalignment of the hinge points on the labels, like below.

from matplotlib.ticker import FuncFormatter

def rad_to_degrees(x, pos):
    'converts radians to degrees'
    return round(x * 57.2985, 2)

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
X = np.linspace(0,2*np.pi,1000)
plt.plot(X,np.sin(X))
plt.plot(X,np.cos(X))

# 1. Adjust x axis Ticks
# 1 radian = 57.2985 degrees
plt.xticks(ticks=np.arange(0, 440/57.2985, 90/57.2985), fontsize=10, rotation=30, ha='center', va='top')  

# 2. Tick Parameters
plt.tick_params(axis='both',bottom=True, top=True, left=True, right=True, direction='in', which='major', grid_color='blue')

# 3. Format tick labels to convert radians to degrees
formatter = FuncFormatter(rad_to_degrees)
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(formatter)
plt.grid(linestyle='--', linewidth=0.5, alpha=0.15)
plt.show()
Matplotlib comes with pre-built colors and palettes.
The common way to make a legend is to define the label parameter for each of the plots using 'plt.legend()'.

# plt.style.use('seaborn-notebook')
plt.figure(figsize=(10,7), dpi=80)
X = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, 1000)
sine = plt.plot(X,np.sin(X)); cosine = plt.plot(X,np.cos(X))
sine_2 = plt.plot(X,np.sin(X+.5)); cosine_2 = plt.plot(X,np.cos(X+.5))
plt.gca().set(ylim=(-1.25, 1.5), xlim=(-.5, 7))

# Modify legend

plt.legend([sine[0], cosine[0], sine_2[0], cosine_2[0]],   # plot items
           ['sine curve', 'cosine curve', 'sine curve 2', 'cosine curve 2'],  
           frameon=True,                                   # legend border
           framealpha=1,                                   # transparency of border
           ncol=2,                                         # num columns
           shadow=True,                                    # shadow on
           borderpad=1,                                    # thickness of border
           title='Sines and Cosines')                      # title
plt.show()

# Texts, Arrows and Annotations Example
# ref: https://matplotlib.org/users/annotations_guide.html
plt.figure(figsize=(12,5), dpi=100)
X = np.linspace(0, 8*np.pi, 1000)
sine = plt.plot(X,np.sin(X), color='tab:blue');

# 1. Annotate with Arrow Props and bbox
plt.annotate('Peaks', xy=(90/57.2985, 1.0), xytext=(90/57.2985, 1.5),
             bbox=dict(boxstyle='square', fc='green', linewidth=0.1),
             arrowprops=dict(facecolor='green', shrink=0.01, width=0.1), 
             fontsize=12, color='white', horizontalalignment='center')

# 2. Texts at Peaks and Troughs
'''
for angle in [440, 810, 1170]:
    plt.text(angle/57.2985, 1.05, str(angle) + "\ndegrees", transform=plt.gca().transData, horizontalalignment='center', color='green')

for angle in [270, 630, 990, 1350]:
    plt.text(angle/57.2985, -1.3, str(angle) + "\ndegrees", transform=plt.gca().transData, horizontalalignment='center', color='red')    

'''
plt.gca().set(ylim=(-2.0, 2.0), xlim=(-.5, 26))
plt.title('Annotations and Texts Example', fontsize=18)
plt.show()
Tow convenient ways to create customized multi-subplots layout. Blow two operation is draw complex layouts.

* plt.subplot2grid :  A helper function that is similar to subplot() but uses 0-based indexing and let subplot to occupy multiple cells.


* plt.GridSpec

ax2 = plt.subplot2grid((3,3), (0,0), colspan=3)
ax3 = plt.subplot2grid((3,3), (1,0), colspan=2)
ax4 = plt.subplot2grid((3,3), (2, 0), colspan=1)
plt.show()

ax1 = plt.subplot2grid((3,3), (0,0), colspan=3)
ax2 = plt.subplot2grid((3,3), (1,0), colspan=2)
ax3 = plt.subplot2grid((3,3), (1,2), rowspan=2)
ax4 = plt.subplot2grid((3,3), (2,0))
ax5 = plt.subplot2grid((3,3), (2,1))

plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
ax1 = plt.subplot2grid((4,4), (0,0), rowspan=3, colspan=4) # Top
ax2 = plt.subplot2grid((4,4), (3,0), rowspan=1, colspan=4) # Bottom
plt.show()

import matplotlib.gridspec as gridspec

gs = gridspec.GridSpec(3,3)
ax1 = plt.subplot(gs[0, :])
ax2 = plt.subplot(gs[1, :-1])
ax3 = plt.subplot(gs[1: , -1])
ax4 = plt.subplot(gs[-1, 0])
ax5 = plt.subplot(gs[-1, -2])
